Turkey said today its disputes withGreece, including rights on the continental shelf in the AegeanSea, should be solved through negotiations.    A Foreign Ministry statement said the latest crisis betweenthe two NATO members stemmed from the continental shelf disputeand an agreement on this issue would effect the security,economy and other rights of both countries.    "As the issue is basicly political, a solution can only befound by bilateral negotiations," the statement said. Greece hasrepeatedly said the issue was legal and could be solved at theInternational Court of Justice.    The two countries approached armed confrontation last monthafter Greece announced it planned oil exploration work in theAegean and Turkey said it would also search for oil.    A face-off was averted when Turkey confined its research toterritorrial waters. "The latest crises created an historicopportunity to solve the disputes between the two countries,"the Foreign Ministry statement said.    Turkey's ambassador in Athens, Nazmi Akiman, was due tomeet Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou today for the Greekreply to a message sent last week by Turkish Prime MinisterTurgut Ozal. The contents of the message were not disclosed. Reuter&#3;